1 wrecker may be equipped with one (1) or more flashing, rotating, or
2 oscillating blue lights, visible under normal atmospheric conditions from a
3 distance of five hundred (500) feet to the rear of the vehicle. The operator of
4 a wrecker may use the blue lights allowed under this paragraph only when
5 the wrecker is stationary and while removing a vehicle or debris from a
6 highway. The operator of a wrecker shall not use blue lights when towing a
7 vehicle on a highway.
8 (5) All Department of Corrections vehicles used as emergency vehicles shall be
9 equipped with one (1) or more flashing, rotating, or oscillating blue lights, visible
10 under normal atmospheric conditions from a distance of five hundred (500) feet to
11 the front of the vehicle. The Department of Corrections vehicles shall not be
12 equipped with or use a siren, whistle, or bell. The equipment prescribed by this
13 subsection shall be in addition to any other equipment required by motor vehicle
14 laws.
15 (6) (a) If authorized by the legislative body of a county, urban-county government,
16 charter county government, consolidated local government, or unified local
17 government:
18 1. All publicly owned county jail and regional jail vehicles used as
19 emergency vehicles may be equipped with the one (1) or more flashing,
20 rotating, or oscillating blue lights, visible under normal atmospheric
21 conditions from a distance of five hundred (500) feet to the front of the
22 vehicle; and
23 2. An elected jailer or the chief administrator of a county or regional jail
24 not managed by an elected jailer may equip one (1) personally owned
25 vehicle with one (1) or more flashing, rotating, or oscillating blue lights,
26 visible under normal atmospheric conditions from a distance of five
27 hundred (500) feet to the front of the vehicle.
